        <div class="content-card">
            <h2>ðŸŒ Autoswitching PSUs</h2>
            
            <div class="simple-box">
                <strong>What is autoswitching?</strong><br>
                A PSU that automatically detects whether you're using 110V (USA) or 230V (Europe) and adjusts itself. You don't need to flip any switches or do anything - it just works!
            </div>
            
            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>PSU Type</th>
                    <th>How It Works</th>
                    <th>Travel Friendly?</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Autoswitching</strong></td>
                    <td>âœ… Automatically detects 100-240V<br>No switches or settings needed</td>
                    <td>âœ… Yes! Use anywhere in the world</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Manual Switch</strong></td>
                    <td>âš ï¸ You must flip switch: 110V or 230V<br>Must match your country!</td>
                    <td>âš ï¸ Yes, but you must set it correctly</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Fixed Voltage</strong></td>
                    <td>âŒ Only works with one voltage<br>110V OR 230V (not both)</td>
                    <td>âŒ No! Only works in certain countries</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
            
            <div class="alert-box danger">
                <span class="alert-icon">ðŸš¨</span>
                <strong>CRITICAL WARNING:</strong> If you have a manual-switch PSU set to 110V and plug it into a 230V outlet (Europe), you will FRY YOUR PSU instantly! Always check before plugging in!
            </div>

            <h2>âš¡ PSU Wattage & Power Requirements</h2>
            
            <div class="simple-box">
                <strong>What is wattage?</strong><br>
                Wattage is the PSU's output capacity - how much total power it can deliver to all your components. More components = need more watts!
            </div>
            
            <h3>Typical Wattage Requirements</h3>
            
            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>Component</th>
                    <th>Power Draw</th>
                    <th>Notes</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Motherboard</strong></td>
                    <td>50-80 watts</td>
                    <td>Pretty consistent across models</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>CPU (Low Power)</strong></td>
                    <td>17-65 watts</td>
                    <td>Office PCs, laptops</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>CPU (Mid-Range)</strong></td>
                    <td>100-150 watts</td>
                    <td>Standard desktop CPUs</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>CPU (High Performance)</strong></td>
                    <td>240-250 watts</td>
                    <td>Gaming CPUs, workstations</td>
